\"text\":\"**Considering Java proxy classes**\\n\\nI'm exploring whether a proxy class can be defined in the same package and if it can access a private nested interface. It seems that Java's dynamic proxies can be created for non-public interfaces, but I'm wondering about the limitations with private nested interfaces. They might generate an IllegalAccessError if accessed improperly. To be safe, maybe I should make nested interfaces public, ensuring that the proxy class can implement them without issues.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring interface access levels**\\n\\nI'm considering changing to a public interface, but that might expose helpers I want to keep private. Maybe I could use a package-private top-level interface instead, but that likely needs to be public. For nested interfaces, I can make them public static since they are static by nature. A private subclass for testing might be a good move, and I would need a protected constructor for the DNSJavaNameService to work properly. Plus, the interface methods can throw exceptions, which aligns with the dynamic proxy behavior.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_rCcWs0mPzw1OY49PgsqnIMqL|fc_0e9602aaccdd11d70169f4dcfed53881918325f63b84b39067", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/dnsjava/dnsjava/2.1.7/src/test/java/dnsjava/dnsjava/DNSJavaNameServiceTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "    private interface ModernNameService {\n", "newText": "    public interface ModernNameService {\n"}, {"oldText": "    private interface LegacyNameService {\n", "newText": "    public interface LegacyNameService {\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1016, "output": 617, "cacheRead": 28672, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30305, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777655027366, "responseId": "resp_0e9602aaccdd11d70169f4dcf3d4588191b10ad6bd26585cca"}}
