[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Java proxy classes**\n\nI'm exploring whether a proxy class can be defined in the same package and if it can access a private nested interface. It seems that Java's dynamic proxies can be created for non-public interfaces, but I'm wondering about the limitations with private nested interfaces. They might generate an IllegalAccessError if accessed improperly. To be safe, maybe I should make nested interfaces public, ensuring that the proxy class can implement them without issues.\n\n**Exploring interface access levels**\n\nI'm considering changing to a public interface, but that might expose helpers I want to keep private. Maybe I could use a package-private top-level interface instead, but that likely needs to be public. For nested interfaces, I can make them public static since they are static by nature. A private subclass for testing might be a good move, and I would need a protected constructor for the DNSJavaNameService to work properly. Plus, the interface methods can throw exceptions, which aligns with the dynamic proxy behavior.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0e9602aaccdd11d70169f4dcf4827c8191b9add4ea6eeda32c\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9Nz-iMxOfrZRWEuuLjDRE40q_CJyq2_wpQcyvA5joB65--3nfknREWGXGZELJwB3-AebEqzH9oIUFD1lxSDs7wlPPGHhxrunCDtlTX1_ROUYsqZjQWA6T7P1ZUYa2cX75gOTLiKz2ek1kWppWywn_KGYPzgeSr9FMSPtgHmYlpNfjb3zKIeBFzGzD1LWDESuETZMwF4Ufxl2PlmLcR-qzY0MbrbNDlpcf_OQDNXSxcV7OrxpyzHtDcn3FjRZmmTfL2COJgIK2SoyNCunhcMdyfOyLBMLdxbPX6wew9U29YhOIycnn_nNYByewY4lk0Ahho24ImSRHEkZaYH5w_PMtbHi0Nldla7rUlySZvbUPe_XRJrw07EyPeDzPm_yEqdYSJaNBBB0YQDmpsuQhWS9azovZlCq_tU0oMqaTHc-oELJAhskXQD56OcgsVR9PXowxGHNeLHtSGJ82Q-V1NQMVNkjdcOx-WUwQi5YbVV80a13d5BQZgzRRrTz0T9io79Xgt50Pnzlm0O2wh6t0Ui6XEBCj0YlQ_vwzXh6FUe0A-t3uwguqzuwoVHXy4ZR6381lY7ZBxySvYjjx1bOkPMtZURwDKAViftiT2Fk88Cb1gCKuFRg9Ip7jE-TXNBX6K2NRylfn4E-Ig76D2w81neqPbzgp3Qcf43yO-_NW_L2H3